<p><br />
<em>BCMI_2</em> with neurofeedback is used in the following projects:</p>

<ol>
  <li>corine protocol</li>
  <li>here and now (revisited)</li>
  <li>berlin - colchester BCMI</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="1-corine-protocol">1. corine protocol</h3>
<p>In this project I have been designing a neurofeedback protocol to be used with <em>BCMI_2</em> between its main two parts, the <a href="/openbci-supercollider-interface/">Open-SuperCollider-Interface</a> (Interface) and the <a href="/shamanic-soundscape-generator/">Shamanic Soundscape Generator</a> (Generator). The protocol is based on Flor-Henry et all.â€™s paper titled â€˜<a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/315988926_Brain_changes_during_a_shamanic_trance_Altered_modes_of_consciousness_hemispheric_laterality_and_systemic_psychobiology">Brain changes during a shamanic trance: Altered modes of consciousness, hemispheric laterality, and systemic psychobiology</a>â€™, where a shamanic practitionerâ€™s, <a href="https://www.corinesombrun.com/en/biography/">Sorine Sombrum</a>â€™s EEG was analysed with qEEG and LORETA methods while she was entering a Shamanic State of Consciousness (SSC). Due to the difference between the amount of channels used in their research (43) and the amount of channels currently available in the Interface (8), the neuromarkers for my <em>corine (neurofeedback) protocol</em> needed certain simplification. This simplification was also needed as the Interface currently does not support LORETA analysis.</p>

<p><img src="../assets/img/20190101-corine-protocol-draft.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>The prototype of this protocol should have been tested at the <a href="https://issuu.com/camscifest/docs/csf_2020_online">2020 Cambridge Science Festival</a>, however due to the pandemic the event was cancelled and now the demonstration needs to be rescheduled.</p>

<p><img src="../assets/img/20200321-cambridge-science-festival-cancelled.jpg" alt="" /></p>

